08084nam a22008415i 9780812298277DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122982777 a10.9783/97808122982772doi  a(DE-B1597)590447  a(OCoLC)1302162643  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPS25 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a810.922300aNeither the Time nor the Place :bThe New Nineteenth-Century American Studies /ced. by Christopher Castiglia, Susan Gillman. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b14 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Citizenship -- tChapter 1. Roma Redux: The Analogical Nineteenth Century -- tChapter 2. African Americans and the Panama Canal Zone as a Third Space -- tChapter 3. “Something Awful in the Voice of the Multitude”: Harriet Beecher Stowe’s Dred on Power and Social Struggle -- tPart II. Environment -- tChapter 4. Uneven Improvement: Swamplands and the Matter of Slavery in Stowe, Northup, and Thoreau -- tChapter 5. Vanishing Sounds: Thoreau and the Sixth Extinction -- tPart III. Historiography -- tChapter 6. Beyond Space: The Speculative Dimension of Nineteenth-Century American Literature -- tChapter 7. Exorbitant Optics and Lunatic Pleasures -- tChapter 8. The Other South: Time, Space, and Counterfactual Histories of the Civil War -- tChapter 9. Apocalypse Then: Southern Speculative Fiction, Slavery, and Civil War, 1836–1860 -- tPart IV. Media -- tChapter 10. Editing Melville’s Pierre: Text, Nation, Time -- tChapter 11. American Literary Studies @ Scale -- tChapter 12. Place Out of Time: LatinX Studies, Migrant Fictions, and Israel Potter -- tPart V. Bodies -- tChapter 13. Shame and the Emotional Life of the Realist Novel -- tChapter 14. Ghosts of Another Time: Spiritualism, Photography, Enchantment -- tChapter 15. Not to Mention: (the marmorean unconscious) -- tNotes -- tList of Contributors -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe usefulness of time and place as defining categories would seem to be baked into the very notion of nineteenth-century American literary studies, yet they have challenged scholars practically since the field's inception. In Neither the Time nor the Place seventeen critics consider how the space-time dyad has both troubled and invigorated Americanist scholarship in recent decades and make explicit how time and place are best considered in tandem, interrogating each other.Taken together, the essays challenge depictions of place and time as bounded and linear, fixed and teleological, or mere ideological constructions. They address both familiar and unexpected objects, practices, and texts, including a born-digital Melville, documents from the construction of the Panama Canal, the hollow earth, the desiring body, textual editing, marble statuary, the sound of frogs, spirit photography, and twentieth-century Civil War fiction. The essays draw on an equally wide variety of critical methodologies, integrating affect studies, queer theory, book history, information studies, sound studies, environmental humanities, new media studies, and genre theory to explore the unexpected dimensions that emerge when time and place are taken as a unit. The pieces are organized around considerations of citizenship, environment, historiography, media, and bodies—five political, cultural, and/or methodological foci for some of the most provocative new work being done in American literary studies.Neither the Time nor the Place is a book not only for scholars and students already well grounded in the study of nineteenth-century American literature and culture, but for anyone, scholar or student, looking for a roadmap to some of the most vibrant work in the field.Contributors: Wai Chee Dimock, Stephanie Foote, Matthew Pratt Guterl, Coleman Hutchison, Rodrigo Lazo, Caroline Levander, Robert S. Levine, Christopher Looby, Dana Luciano, Timothy Marr, Dana D. Nelson, Ifeoma C. Kiddoe Nwankwo, Mark Storey, Matthew E. Suazo, and Edward Sugden.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.1 aCastiglia, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastiglia, Christopher, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDimock, Wai Chee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoote, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGillman, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGillman, Susan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGuterl, Matthew Pratt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutchison, Coleman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLazo, Rodrigo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevander, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevine, Robert S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLooby, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuciano, Dana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarr, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNelson, Dana D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNwankwo, Ifeoma C. Kiddoe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStorey, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSuaz